{"type":"text","timestamp":1777215741646,"sessionID":"ses_235b0323cffeqgm5ipNnqxGUPj","part":{"id":"prt_dca4ff4b0001z6HFSKaiQLk1T0","messageID":"msg_dca4fcfa9001Y1zGF07Ldc7a6O","sessionID":"ses_235b0323cffeqgm5ipNnqxGUPj","type":"text","text":"**Event Sourcing vs Traditional CRUD — Order Management**\n\n| Dimension | Event Sourcing | Traditional CRUD |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Consistency** | Eventual consistency by default; strong consistency requires CQRS/aggregate design. Audit trail is inherent. | Strong consistency by default (ACID). Audit requires separate change tracking. |\n| **Query Performance** | Read-side is optimized via materialized views (CQRS). Event replay for ad-hoc queries is slow. | Simple indexed queries. Ad-hoc reporting is straightforward. |\n| **Learning Curve** | **High** — event modeling, CQRS, projections, snapshots, event versioning, eventual consistency mindset. | **Low** — standard ORM, well-understood patterns, abundant tooling. |\n| **Scalability** | **Excellent** — append-only event store scales writes naturally. Read models scale independently. | Writes scale via sharding (complex with ACID). Reads scale with replicas/caches. |\n| **Ops Cost** | **Higher** — event store + projection DBs + schema evolution tooling + replay infrastructure + monitoring. | **Lower** — single DB, mature monitoring, simpler backups. |\n\n**Recommendation: Traditional CRUD** (confidence: 82%)\n\nFor an order management system, the dominant concern is consistency (orders must never be lost or double-processed) and operational simplicity. The audit and scalability benefits of event sourcing are real but don't justify the complexity premium unless you already have:\n\n- High-throughput (>10K events/sec) writes\n- Complex, cross-service workflows requiring replay\n- Regulatory requirements demanding full state history\n\nOtherwise, CRUD with a dedicated audit log table covers 90%+ of order management needs at a fraction of the cost.","time":{"start":1777215741640,"end":1777215741640}}}
